    "Run vs Walk Activity Classification Report\n",
    "1. Introduction:\n",
    "Human activity recognition using wearable sensor data plays an important role in fitness tracking, healthcare monitoring, and sports analytics. In this project, the objective was to classify walking and running activities using sensor data by applying thorough exploratory data analysis, feature engineering, and multiple deep learning models. The focus was not only on achieving high accuracy but also on understanding the data behavior and selecting the most appropriate model based on temporal characteristics.\n",
    "2. Dataset Understanding and Initial Processing:\n",
    "After importing all required libraries, the dataset was loaded and basic inspections were performed to understand its structure, data types, and completeness. Non-sensor columns that did not contribute to activity classification were removed to reduce noise and prevent bias in the model.\n",
    "Challenge Faced:\n",
    "Some columns contained metadata rather than motion information, which could mislead the model.\n",
    "Technique Used & Reason:\n",
    "Dropping non-sensor columns helped ensure the model learned only from meaningful motion signals, improving generalization and interpretability.\n",
    "3. Class Distribution Analysis:\n",
    "The class distribution of walking and running activities was visualized to verify dataset balance.\n",
    "Challenge Faced:\n",
    "An imbalanced dataset could lead to biased predictions favoring the dominant class.\n",
    "Technique Used & Reason:\n",
    "Class distribution visualization confirmed that both activities were sufficiently represented, eliminating the need for resampling techniques.\n",
    "4. Feature Engineering Acceleration Magnitude:\n",
    "A new feature, acceleration magnitude, was derived from raw sensor axes to capture overall movement intensity.\n",
    "Challenge Faced:\n",
    "Individual axis signals did not fully represent motion strength.\n",
    "Technique Used & Reason:\n",
    "Acceleration magnitude was computed to combine multi-axis information into a single meaningful metric, improving separability between walking and running.\n",
    "5. Time Series Visualization:\n",
    "Raw sensor signals were visualized over time for both activities.\n",
    "Challenge Faced:\n",
    "Understanding temporal patterns directly from numerical data was difficult.\n",
    "Technique Used & Reason:\n",
    "Time series plots helped reveal clear differences in signal frequency and amplitude between walking and running, validating the importance of temporal modeling.\n",
    "6. Distribution Analysis (Walking vs Running):\n",
    "Feature distributions were plotted separately for walking and running.\n",
    "Challenge Faced:\n",
    "Overlapping distributions could reduce classification effectiveness.\n",
    "Technique Used & Reason:\n",
    "Distribution plots helped identify features with strong discriminative power, guiding further feature selection and modeling decisions.\n",
    "7. Outlier Detection and Treatment:\n",
    "Outliers were counted per feature and detected using the Interquartile Range (IQR) method.\n",
    "Challenge Faced:\n",
    "Extreme sensor values caused by noise or sensor malfunction could distort learning.\n",
    "Technique Used & Reason:\n",
    "IQR-based outlier detection was chosen because it is robust to non-normal distributions.\n",
    "Extreme outliers were removed to stabilize training and improve model robustness.\n",
    "8. Correlation and Feature Interaction Analysis:\n",
    "A correlation heatmap and pair plots were used to analyze feature relationships.\n",
    "Challenge Faced:\n",
    "Highly correlated features could lead to redundancy and overfitting.\n",
    "Technique Used & Reason:\n",
    "Correlation heatmap identified strong dependencies.\n",
    "Pair plots provided insights into feature interactions and class separability.\n",
    "9. Activity-Wise Statistical Comparison:\n",
    "Statistical metrics were computed separately for walking and running.\n",
    "Challenge Faced:\n",
    "Numerical differences were not obvious without summary statistics.\n",
    "Technique Used & Reason:\n",
    "Activity-wise statistical comparison highlighted consistent differences in motion intensity and variability, strengthening confidence in feature relevance.\n",
    "10. Sliding Window Feature Extraction:\n",
    "A sliding window approach was applied to segment the time-series data.\n",
    "Challenge Faced:\n",
    "Single sensor readings failed to capture temporal dynamics.\n",
    "Technique Used & Reason:\n",
    "Sliding window segmentation preserved temporal continuity and provided richer contextual information for deep learning models.\n",
    "11. Data Scaling:\n",
    "Training and testing data were scaled separately.\n",
    "Challenge Faced:\n",
    "Unscaled features with different ranges slowed convergence and affected model stability.\n",
    "Technique Used & Reason:\n",
    "Feature scaling ensured uniform contribution of all features and improved optimization during training.\n",
    "12. Model Training\n",
    "Three models were trained:\n",
    "ANN\n",
    "FNN / MLP\n",
    "1D Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)\n",
    "All models achieved an accuracy of 1.0 on the test data.\n",
    "Observations:\n",
    "ANN: Simple and fast, but ignores temporal structure.\n",
    "FNN/MLP: Easy to train, but shares the same limitation as ANN and is less scalable.\n",
    "1D-CNN: Learns temporal patterns effectively, slightly heavier computationally, but better suited for time-series sensor data.\n",
    "13. Model Comparison and Discussion:\n",
    "Despite identical accuracy scores, model selection was based on data characteristics rather than performance alone. Since the dataset is time-series in nature, models that capture temporal dependencies are more reliable in real-world scenarios.\n",
